    - m_Type: 0
      Title:
        m_Untranslated: Lines 17, 24, and 31 - If Statements and Reading Input
      Text:
        m_Untranslated: "<code>\r\n// Spin counter-clockwise if A or left arrow is
          pressed\r\nif (Keyboard.current.aKey.isPressed || Keyboard.current.leftArrowKey.isPressed)\r\n\r\n...\r\n\r\n//
          Spin clockwise if D or right arrow is pressed\r\nif (Keyboard.current.dKey.isPressed
          || Keyboard.current.rightArrowKey.isPressed)\r\n\r\n...\r\n\r\n// When
          W or the up arrow is pressed, apply thrust to the ship\r\nif (Keyboard.current.wKey.isPressed
          || Keyboard.current.upArrowKey.isPressed)\r\n</code>\r\nInside the FixedUpdate
          function, there are a number of if-statements to make certain actions occur
          when the associated inputs are given (these if-statements are on <b>lines
          17, 24, and 31</b>). For reference, the syntax of an if-statement in C#
          is:\r\n<code>\r\nif (condition)\r\n{\r\n    //code to run if condition
          is true\r\n}\r\n</code>\r\nThe condition for an if statement is a boolean
          (true or false), which may be the value returned from a function, a variable,
          or by comparing a variable to another value (e.g. <c>i \\< 5</c>). As with
          functions, the code to run if the condition is true is contained between
          the opening and closing curly braces.\r\nUnity's new Input System has a class called <doc>Keyboard</doc>
          that contains a number of properties for reading input. In this method we
          want the player to rotate and thrust when specific keys are held down (i.e.
          for every game update that the key is pressed we want to player to move).
          The <doc>Keyboard.current.key.isPressed</doc> property is perfect for this. The first if-statement
          checks to see if either the left arrow key or A key is currently being
          pressed and if so rotates the player counter-clockwise (to the left). Similarly,
          the second if-statement checks if the right arrow key or D key is being
          pressed, and rotates the player clockwise.\r\nSee the following for more
          explanation of if-statements and the Keyboard class:\r\n\u2022 If statements:
          <a>https://unity3d.com/learn/tutorials/topics/scripting/if-statements?playlist=17117</a>\r\n\u2022
          Keyboard Input: <a>https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.inputsystem@1.0/manual/Keyboard.html</a>\r\n"
